<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-176  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 176.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 19 1990 v4 n7 p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FBI to launch drug investigative system. (the Federal Bureau ofInvestigation's Drug Information System will search three FBIinvestigative databases at once to battle drug traffickingcartels)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Bureau of Investigation's Drug Information System(DIS), which will be installed starting in Mar 1990, is intendedto let agents use powerful intelligent workstations to searchthree FBI investigative databases at one time.andP;  Records from thethree databases will be displayed on-screen side-by-side by thesystem, along with photographs, surveillance photographs of areasunder investigation, maps of the flow of drugs into the US andtime line charts showing relationships between drug traffickers.andO;DIS includes a resources management system that tells users whichavailable agents have special skills and a financial managementsystem that reports on how much money is available to spend oninformants, vehicles and other expenses; money launderingtemplates help trace the process of cleaning drug cash.andP;  Imageenhancement for surveillance photos, fingerprint identificationand city maps showing drug trafficking areas will be added to thesystem over time.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Drug AbuseLaw EnforcementGovernment AgencyNational GovernmentInformation Resources ManagementData Base Management SystemsIntegrated SystemsImage ProcessingUnited States. Federal Bureau of Investigation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>